# =============================================================================
# X++ MCP Server — legacy configuration file
# =============================================================================
# You no longer configure this server by editing .env. Run:
#
#     npm run setup
#
# The wizard asks only what your deployment scenario needs (each question comes
# with an explanation), then writes:
#
#     config/d365fo-mcp.json   — all settings, grouped by area
#     config/secrets.json      — connection strings / API keys, owner-only
#
# Every setting, its default and the environment variable it maps to is
# documented in docs/CONFIGURATION.md — generated from the same registry the
# wizard uses (src/config/settings.ts), so it cannot drift.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Still using a .env?
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# It keeps working: the server reads it as a fallback for anything the JSON
# config does not define. `npm run setup` imports the values it finds here, and
# `d365fo-mcp doctor` reports any key where the two files disagree (the JSON
# config wins). Once the JSON config is complete, this file can be deleted.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Running several instances from one clone
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#   d365fo-mcp instance add            — creates instances/<name>/d365fo-mcp.json
#   D365FO_CONFIG=<path to json> node dist/index.js
#   D365FO_CONFIG=<path to json> npm run build-database
#
# ENV_FILE=<path to a .env> is still honoured for legacy setups.
# =============================================================================
